## Abstract
This document describes a standard interface to fork ERC20 and other types of tokens in a new contract.

## Motivation
If, for example, I have **100 ATKN**, but the ATKN smart contract has a degree of centralization unacceptable to me, a backdoor or any error that could cause the loss of money. Assuming the contract is open source, I could talk to others who noticed the same error or who have the same ideological difference with the smart contract as me. We could edit the source code of the contract and deploy it, launching the **OTKN** token. But, why would we do that? Our new OTKN token would have no value. And we would have _x_ ATKN and 0 OTKN. We must sell our ATKN tokens and buy OTKN tokens. This would not work, because no exchange has included our new token.

This standard was created with the intention of solving this or similar problems, such as updating smart contracts.

## Specification
**NOTES**:
  + The following specifications use syntax from Solidity 0.5.11 (or above).

### Constants
#### forkOf
```solidity
address public forkOf;
```
**Only for forked tokens**: Specifies the address of the forked token when creating the current token.

#### currentSupply
```solidity
uint256 public currentSupply;
```
Specifies the current supply of the tokens.

### Methods
#### claimTokens
```solidity
function claimTokens() public returns (bool success);
```
**Only for forked tokens**: If ```balanceOf(msg.sender)``` is 0, adds the quantity of tokens of ```msg.sender``` at the [```forkOf```](#forkof) address to its balances and calls the [```giveTokens()```](#givetokens) function of the contract at the [```forkOf```](#forkOf) address. Additionaly, fires the [```TokensClaimed()```](#tokensclaimed) event.

#### giveTokens
```solidity
function giveTokens() public returns (bool success);
```
Burns tokens of ```tx.origin``` at ```address(this)``` address. Additionaly, fires the [```TokensGiven()```](#tokensgiven) event.

### Events
#### TokensClaimed
```solidity
event TokensClaimed(address _owner);
```

#### TokensGiven
```solidity
event TokensGiven(address _owner);
```

## Implementation
```solidity
pragma solidity ^0.5.11;

interface IForkableToken
{
    function giveTokens() external returns (bool success);
    event TokensGiven(address _owner);
}

interface IForkedToken
{
    function claimTokens() external returns (bool success);
    event TokensClaimed(address _owner);
}

contract ForkedForkableExampleToken is IForkedToken, IForkableToken
{
    using SafeMath for uint256;

    address public forkOf;
    uint256 public currentSupply;
    mapping (address => uint256) private balances;
    
    constructor() public
    {
        // ...
        forkOf = address(0x0123456789abcdef /* ... */);
        currentSupply = 0;
        // ...
    }
    
    /* ... */
    
    function claimTokens() public returns (bool success)
    {
        IForkableToken forkableOriginalToken = IForkableToken(forkOf);
        IERC20 erc20OriginalToken = IERC20(forkOf);
        require(balanceOf(msg.sender) == 0x00);
        uint256 originalBalance = erc20OriginalToken.balanceOf();
        require(forkableOriginalToken.giveTokens() == true);
        balances[msg.sender] = originalBalance;
        currentSupply = currentSupply.add(originalBalance);
        emit TokensClaimed(msg.sender);
        return true;
    }

    function giveTokens() public returns (bool success)
    {
        balances[tx.origin] = 0x00;
        currentSupply = currentSupply.sub(balanceOf(tx.origin));
        emit TokensGiven(tx.origin);
        return true;
    }

    /* ... */

    event TokensClaimed(address _owner);
    event TokensGiven(address _owner);
}
```

